english:
  title: A Letter in Response to a Certain Records Keeper
  author: Lee Gyeong-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On this day, I bow my head to you, my dear friend.

    Last when we parted ways, you kindly rode through the humble threshold of my modest home. Yet the wine was thin and day grew dim—our farewell was not as generous as it ought to have been. I am ashamed and full of regret. Still, knowing as you do my constrained circumstances, I trust you harbor no suspicion.

    Your letter asks: what is most urgent in governing a county? I laughed and replied: Does not the ancient text say, "A general who has lost the battle cannot speak of courage"? I am one who failed to complete my term governing Jeonju. Where would I have the face to discourse on the priorities of statecraft? And yet—you do not deem me foolish or ignorant, nor do you hold yourself superior. Instead you ask me in trust about your doubts. How could I not answer you plainly? For to withhold truth would be to deny the sincere affection between us.

    Allow me to speak one truth: in governing a county, there is nothing beyond achieving the right balance between leniency and severity. In my time administering Jeonju, harsh measures became well-known, yet I tell you this is not the whole picture of how I governed. But governance is not one-size-fits-all. One must first observe the character of the people, then calibrate severity and leniency accordingly—this is paramount.

    Jeonju is the ancient land of Baekje, and its people are fierce by nature. They cannot be governed by indulgence alone, so I employed punishment—not from my true heart, but from necessity. Yet those who understood nothing called me cruel. But consider: in lands unlike Jeonju, severity alone will scatter the people like dust, while indulgence alone makes them slack and complacent. Only by alternating between firmness and gentleness do they revere you as a spirit and love you as a parent. There is no people thus treated who cannot be governed well.

    This is not beyond your own understanding either. I share merely what I have held in my heart. Yet words are easy; action is hard. This teaching, though simple, is the most difficult to practice in actual governance. Do not take it lightly.

    You also request the memorials and statutes I wrote while in Jeonju. Alas, I failed to preserve them at that time, so I cannot send them to you. I beg your forgiveness. Instead, I offer this small token: white silk paper as you requested and forty fine bamboo arrows, merely to wish you safe travels.

    With humble respect, I bow again.
  footnotes:
    - Jeonju (完山), also known as Jeonju, was a significant administrative region during the Goryeo period and is the ancient land of the kingdom of Baekje.
    - The reference to "a general who has lost the battle" is from Chinese classical texts, expressing the modesty topos common in Korean literati culture.
    - The concept of balancing "leniency and severity" (寬猛) reflects Confucian governance philosophy, particularly the idea that different populations require different approaches.
